That I could take a periodic function,

00:00:05.348 --> 00:00:07.135
we started with the example of

00:00:07.135 --> 00:00:09.210
this square wave, and that I could

00:00:09.210 --> 00:00:12.793
represent it as the sum of weighted

00:00:12.793 --> 00:00:14.293
sines and cosines.

00:00:15.232 --> 00:00:16.291
And then we took a little bit of

00:00:16.291 --> 00:00:18.321
an interlude of building up

00:00:18.321 --> 00:00:20.800
some of our mathematical foundations,

00:00:20.800 --> 00:00:23.117
just establishing a bunch of properties

00:00:23.117 --> 00:00:24.658
of taking the definite integral

00:00:24.658 --> 00:00:28.032
over the period of that periodic function

00:00:28.032 --> 00:00:30.511
of sine and cosines and we established

00:00:30.511 --> 00:00:32.055
all of these properties.

00:00:32.055 --> 00:00:33.638
And now we're going to get the benefit

00:00:33.638 --> 00:00:35.265
from establishing all those because

00:00:35.265 --> 00:00:37.174
we're going to start actually finding

00:00:37.174 --> 00:00:39.732
at least a formula for
Fourier coefficients

00:00:39.732 --> 00:00:40.871
and then we can apply it to our

00:00:40.871 --> 00:00:42.334
original square wave to see that, hey,

00:00:42.334 --> 00:00:43.877
this could actually be a pretty

00:00:43.877 --> 00:00:45.499
straightforward thing.

00:00:45.499 --> 00:00:48.097
So right over here, I have rewritten

00:00:48.097 --> 00:00:50.905
a Fourier series expression,

00:00:50.905 --> 00:00:52.323
or I've rewritten a Fourier series

00:00:52.323 --> 00:00:54.636
for a periodic function f(t),

00:00:54.636 --> 00:00:57.278
let's say its period is 2π,

00:00:57.278 --> 00:00:58.496
and I'm going to use this in some

00:00:58.496 --> 00:01:00.769
of the properties that we have established

00:01:00.769 --> 00:01:05.236
to start solving for
these actual coefficients.

00:01:05.236 --> 00:01:06.904
And what I'm gonna do in this video,

00:01:06.904 --> 00:01:08.126
I'm gonna first try to solve for

00:01:08.126 --> 00:01:09.508
a-sub-0 and then in the next video,

00:01:09.508 --> 00:01:12.631
we're gonna solve for
an arbitrary a-sub-n.

00:01:12.631 --> 00:01:13.813
And either in that one or the next one,

00:01:13.813 --> 00:01:17.594
we'll also solve for an arbitrary b-sub-n.

00:01:17.594 --> 00:01:19.417
So to solve for a-sub-0,

00:01:19.417 --> 00:01:21.695
what we're going to do is take

00:01:21.695 --> 00:01:23.524
the definite integral of both sides

00:01:23.524 --> 00:01:25.349
from 0 to 2π.

00:01:25.349 --> 00:01:28.726
So 0 to 2π, dt of f(t),

00:01:28.726 --> 00:01:30.106
well that's gonna be the same thing

00:01:30.106 --> 00:01:31.856
as going from 0 to 2π

00:01:33.073 --> 00:01:35.141
of all of this stuff.

00:01:35.141 --> 00:01:36.525
And remember, this is an infinite

00:01:36.525 --> 00:01:37.579
series right over here,

00:01:37.579 --> 00:01:39.123
we have an infinite number of terms.

00:01:39.123 --> 00:01:41.679
And then we would have a dt out there.

00:01:41.679 --> 00:01:44.031
But we know from our
integration properties,

00:01:44.031 --> 00:01:45.735
taking the definite integral of

00:01:45.735 --> 00:01:47.685
a sum, even an infinite sum,

00:01:47.685 --> 00:01:49.189
is the same thing as the sum of

00:01:49.189 --> 00:01:50.487
the definite integrals.

00:01:50.487 --> 00:01:52.032
So that's going to be the same thing

00:01:52.032 --> 00:01:54.032
as taking this integral,

00:01:55.371 --> 00:01:57.204
dt plus this integral.

